Leyline & Lunacy: How Two Idiots Nearly Got Themselves Erased From Reality

Arkäne

Morning comes reluctantly to Arkäne, as it always does. He cracks open his grey eyes with the same enthusiasm one reserves for tax audits, watching the pale light filter through the high dormitory windows. The water temple’s bells toll faintly in the distance—Quìjja’s call. He exhales through his nose, rubs the sleep from his eyes, and rises with the stiff grace of someone who’d rather be horizontal.

 

The gloves go on first, always. Soft black leather, well-fitted, never removed except in absolute solitude. No one needs to know what stains these hands carry. The rest of his attire follows—light scholar’s robes, crisply pressed, embroidered with gold thread that catches the predawn light. Practical, presentable. Not that he cares much for appearances, but nobility demands its petty sacrifices.

 

Tea is necessary. Arkäne sets a kettle to boil over the small brazier in his room, grinding dried herbs between his fingers. He doesn’t need to ward the door shut—the other students learned quickly that knocking before noon is a poor life decision—but he does it anyway. Old habits.

 

His morning lectures pass in a blur of dry academia and stifled yawns. He tolerates the chatter of his peers with the patience of a man counting to ten—and then to twenty, just to be safe. Occasionally, someone glances at his gloved hands and asks, as if it hasn’t been asked a hundred times before:

 

“Why the gloves, Helsberg?”

 

Arkäne doesn’t pause in taking notes. “Contrary to rumor, I don’t have claws. Just an abiding hatred for ink stains.” His tone is smooth, bored, daring the asker to press further. They never do.

 

He ducks the midday meal in favor of the library, where shadowed stacks offer more companionship than the dining hall’s din. A tome on advanced Mysth theory lies open before him, finger tracing the lines as he memorizes the patterns. A quill moves in slow, precise arcs beside it—notes for a paper, perhaps, or something less academic.

 

By evening, he’s back in his dorm, stirring a pot over a small, warded fire. Stewed herbs, roasted meat, the scent trapped neatly within his wards. You’d think scholars would have something better to do than sniff at doors. Meadr knocks exactly twice before barging in, as is their arrangement, and the rare, faint warmth in Arkäne’s expression isn’t just from the steam.

 

“Don’t hover,” he says, nudging a bowl toward his friend. “It’s not poisoned. Probably.”

 

Meadr

“Probably?” Meadr repeats, flashing a warm, lopsided grin as he takes the proffered bowl. His golden eyes crinkle at the edges—foxlike, though he only lets that resemblance slip when alone. He lifts the stew to his nose, inhaling deeply before sighing appreciatively. “Ah, there’s the real reason I tolerate you. A noble who can actually cook.”

 

He perches on the edge of Arkäne’s desk, bowl balanced neatly between both hands, posture relaxed but subtly angled toward the door—habit. The enchanted necklace weighs nothing against his collarbone, yet its presence hums in his awareness as always. Safe. Contained.

 

Between spoonfuls, he nods toward Arkäne’s gloves—today’s pair a deep, inky black. “Ink stains, hm? I figured it was just your usual flair for dramatics. Next you’ll tell me you sleep with them on.” He tilts his head, smirk dancing at the corner of his lips. “Unless you do, in which case, well, that’s between you and your tailor.”

 

Meadr’s tone is airy, teasing, but his fingers flex slightly over the bowl. The topic is familiar, like an old dance—an offhand joke masking genuine curiosity beneath. He knows better than to press (they both have their reasons for secrets), but the question lingers in the lilt of his voice.

 

When Arkäne inevitably deflects again, he’ll let it go. He always does. For now, he nudges the conversation along with a safer subject, gesturing toward the open tome on the desk. “Still pouring over those leyline theories? Or just preparing another lecture to put the underclassmen to sleep?” His grin widens—a dare. “Rhezua might actually fight you if you upstage her again in Mysth Law.”

 

Arkäne

Arkäne scoffs, stirring the pot with deliberate laziness before turning to fix Meadr with a look that could freeze a lesser man in place. “Sleeping in gloves? Please. Even my dramatics have standards.” He lifts the spoon, inspecting it with exaggerated scrutiny. “And here I thought you had at least some sense of decency, Meadr. First you barge into my room, then you suggest I wear my gloves to bed like some kind of paranoid hermit.”

 

He ladles a generous portion of stew into Meadr’s bowl—because despite his tone, the redhead knows him well enough to recognize this as a silent ‘stay, I don’t entirely despise your company.’

 

At the mention of Rhezua, his lip twitches—though whether in amusement or annoyance is difficult to tell. “Ah yes, Rhezua. The great tragedy of her existence is that I exist first.” A sardonic sip of his own tea. “If she wants to challenge me in Mysth Law, she’s welcome to try. It’s hardly my fault the Obottá cursed her with less competent tutors.”

 

He eyes the open tome, expression shifting to something contemplative—closer to his true self than the mask of detached arrogance. “Leyline mapping, actually. There’s a hypothesis in the Northern Archives about using minor nexus points as temporary wards. Faster than chanting, more precise than weaving. If I can—”

 

He cuts himself off abruptly, as if catching the rare slip of enthusiasm before it could be fully exposed. Clearing his throat, he flicks a speck of nonexistent dust off his sleeve, mouth settling back into its usual mild disinterest.

 

“—Anyway. You wouldn’t care. History’s more your specialty.” A pause, then, with just the barest hint of dry amusement: “Unless you’re finally taking an interest in practical applications beyond which leyline makes the best shortcut back from festivals?”

 

Meadr

Meadr lets out a warm laugh, the kind that lingers like sunlight in a quiet room. “Cursed her with less competent tutors, he says,” he echoes, shaking his head. “You do realize you sound like the antagonist in half the ballads they sing in the lower quarters, don’t you? Next you'll be monologuing about the insufferable mediocrity of peasantry.”

 

He swirls the stew in his bowl, leaning forward just slightly. Arkäne’s rare flickers of unchecked interest never escape him—he catalogues them like prized artifacts. “Leyline wards, huh? Sounds useful. Especially if they could be deployed mid-conflict without all that tedious chanting.” A pause, then a playful smirk. “Though I did hear that Demír managed to singe his eyebrows off trying something similar last week. Maybe don’t skip the chants entirely.”

 

The mention of shortcuts earns another grin, though his fingers brush the hollow of his throat absently—habit. “Festival routes are practical applications, thank you very much. Not all of us enjoy looming over books like brooding specters.” He tilts his head. “But if you’re desperate for a field test, I suppose I could be convinced to scout a nexus point with you. Provided you don’t plan to blow anything up. Or lecture me about proper academic rigor while we walk.”

 

He takes a deliberate bite, chewing slowly before adding, softer: “Besides. If Rhezua’s watching, it’ll annoy her twice as much if you’ve got company.” His tone is light, but the offer is genuine beneath the teasing—a carefully crafted opening, just ambiguous enough to retreat from if Arkäne bristles.

 

Arkäne

Arkäne arches a brow, stirring his tea with the air of a man who absolutely does loom over books like a brooding specter—and enjoys it. “Field tests are for scholars who lack the imagination to conduct proper research indoors,” he mutters, though there's a flicker of consideration in his gaze. “...But if your delicate festival sensibilities require fresh air, I suppose I could sacrifice an afternoon. For science.”

 

A pause. A sip. Then, dry as parchment: “And Demír singeing his eyebrows off was inevitable. The man tries to weave Mysth like he’s tossing grain to pigeons.” His lips twitch—almost a smile, if one squinted. “Rest assured, I have no intentions of resembling a partially plucked songbird. Unlike some.”

 

He sets the teacup down with exaggerated precision. “As for Rhezua—let her watch. It’s not my fault she finds existence without an audience so difficult.” He flips a page in the tome without looking, feigning indifference, but the corner of his mouth tilts upward when Meadr leans in. “...Fine. Tomorrow. But if you complain about the walk, I’m abandoning you at the first nexus point.”

 

Then, quieter: “Bring bread. The dense kind. If we’re testing wards, you might as well be useful.”

 

Meadr

Meadr beams—an expression just shy of triumphant, the sort that could make a cynic believe in sunshine. “Aha! So you do admit fresh air has its merits,” he teases, pointing his spoon in Arkäne’s direction with playful accusation. “Don’t worry, I’ll protect your scholarly dignity from the horrors of grass and sky.” His voice drops to a stage whisper, eyes glinting. “And if anyone asks, we can say you were lured outside against your will. Kidnapped by a rogue historian with a terrifying surplus of charm.”

 

The mention of Demír’s mishap earns a snort. “Pigeons would’ve at least scattered with some dignity,” he agrees, before pausing to mimic Arkäne’s most deadpan lecture voice: ’Mysth-weaving is not a tavern brawl, Demír, kindly stop flailing.’ Then, back to his usual mirth: “Though honestly, at this point, I think singed eyebrows might be an improvement. They’d give his face some much-needed character.”

 

Bread is an easy promise. Meadr nods, already mentally rifling through the bakery stalls near the institute’s eastern gate. “Dense loaf, got it. Anything to spare the world the tragic sight of Arkäne Helsberg, felled by low blood sugar mid-ward.” He taps his chin. “Should I pack honey too? Or would that be too decadent for field research?”

 

Beneath the banter, though, he catches the near-smile—the unspoken concession—and files it away like a rare tome. He’ll burn this moment to memory later, alone in his room, when the necklace comes off and his thoughts dare to wander. For now, he merely nudges Arkäne’s boot with his own under the desk, fleeting and deliberate.

 

“Don’t look so dour. Who knows? Maybe we’ll uncover a leyline that leads straight to a hidden cache of first-edition Eltherion Scrolls.” His grin turns conspiratorial. “...Or at least a shortcut to that bakery that sells the spiced fig tarts.”

 

Arkäne

“Tarts,” Arkäne echoes, in the same tone one might use to describe a particularly gruesome tax audit. “Because nothing says groundbreaking academic research like pastries. I can already see the thesis title—'On the Correlation Between Leyline Flux and the Optimal Flakiness of Baked Goods.' Truly, Meadr, your scholarly rigor paralyzes me with awe.”

 

He rolls his eyes but—damn him—there’s no real bite to it. His fingers drum once against the desk before he abruptly snaps the tome shut, as if belatedly remembering he’s supposed to be aloof. “Fine. Bring your tarts. But if this expedition devolves into yet another of your scenic detours, I will leave you in the nearest leyline nexus as an impromptu Mysth conductor.”

 

A pause. Then, with the air of a man reluctantly admitting defeat: “And pack extra honey. For—” He gestures vaguely, nearly knocking over his tea. “Contingencies.”

 

(He does not specify what kind. Meadr will know. Meadr always knows.)

 

Meadr

Meadr leans back, shoulders shaking with silent laughter—eyes alight with the kind of mischief that made lesser nobles sigh and professors take measured, cautious steps backward. “Oh, obviously,” he drawls, sweeping a dramatic hand across an imaginary title page. “'A Sweetener's Guide to Leylines: Saccharine Solutions for the Academic Soul.' Groundbreaking, really. I expect an honorary professorship by week's end.”

 

His boots drop from the desk with a soft thud as he straightens, fingers brushing briefly against his hidden necklace—once, like a talisman—before he mock-salutes Arkäne. “Scenic detour? Me? Never.” The grin softens at the edges, betraying his sincerity. “But just in case—I'll leave a trail of breadcrumbs. Honeyed ones, naturally. Wouldn't want you lecturing the local squirrels about proper pathfinding etiquette in my absence.”

 

He pauses at the door, tossing a final look over his shoulder—golden eyes glinting like summer-warmed copper in the dim light. “Until tomorrow, then. Try not to fret too much about it. Wouldn’t want you showing up over-prepared.” The teasing is deliberate, barbless. A familiar dance.

 

(He will, of course, pack extra honey. He always does.)

 

“Alddám, Arkäne.” The door clicks shut behind him, muffling the hum of his laughter—leaving behind only the faintest lingering scent of cinnamon and something earthier, warmer.

 

 

 

Arkäne

Arkäne watches the door close for a beat too long before returning to his research. The candlelight flickers across his impassive face as he scribbles notes with one hand and absently stirs the cooling tea with the other.

 

“Leylines and fig tarts,” he mutters under his breath with a quiet scoff. “What fresh academic hell have I agreed to?”

 

Yet his fingers pause mid-sentence, hovering over the page where he'd been detailing ward schematics. After a moment, he flips to a fresh sheet and—with deliberate, precise strokes—begins sketching a rough map of the nearest accessible leyline nexus, marking potential shortcuts to the bakery district in the margins with far more thoroughness than strictly necessary.

 

For contingencies.

 

Arkäne

The path to the nearest leyline nexus winds through the eastern ridge of the Arx valley, where early morning fog still clings stubbornly between the pines. Arkäne stands at the trailhead, arms crossed, the gold embroidery on his scholar’s robe catching the pale light. His expression is, as always, perfectly neutral—but there’s a faint tension in his jaw that suggests he’s already regretting this arrangement.

 

The soft crunch of approaching footsteps makes him turn.

 

“You’re late,” he says, voice flat. “And bearing baked goods, I see. How predictable.” His eyes flick to the cloth-wrapped parcel under Meadr’s arm, then back up, unimpressed. “Let’s hope your punctuality improves when we’re dealing with volatile energy currents. I’d hate to have to write your epitaph: 'Died waiting for pastries. Rest in crumbs.'”

 

The words are sharp, but he steps aside to let Meadr fall into step beside him, already scanning the terrain ahead with the focused air of someone determined to feign indifference to camaraderie. Only when Meadr isn’t looking does his gloved finger tap—just once—against the folded leyline map in his pocket.

 

(It includes the bakery detour. Obviously.)

 

Meadr

Meadr bounds up the path with all the grace of a fox who's just spotted an unattended picnic basket—his messenger bag slung haphazardly over one shoulder, the promised honey and fig tarts wrapped carefully in waxed cloth. The morning light catches the red in his hair and turns it molten as he flashes a distinctly unrepentant grin.

 

“Late? I prefer fashionably delayed,” he counters, tapping a finger against his temple with exaggerated solemnity. “A strategic trait when dealing with researchers who forget to eat unless forcibly reminded.” He holds out the bundle like a peace offering, though his eyes dance with mischief. “And these aren't just any pastries—they're vital leyline-testing equipment. A scholar of your caliber should know proper research requires sustenance.”

 

As they begin walking, he falls into step beside Arkäne with practiced ease—close enough to converse, but not enough to crowd. His gaze flicks to the dense pine shadows ahead, then back to his companion. “So,” he says brightly, lowering his voice to a conspiratorial hush, “are we pretending this is purely academic, or can I admit I'm mostly here for the view?” His elbow nudges Arkäne's lightly. The view could mean the valley. The leyline shimmer. The rare, unguarded crinkle at the corner of Arkäne's eyes when he begrudgingly accepts the absurdity of this whole outing.

 

Meadr doesn't specify. He's always preferred leaving room for interpretation.

 

 

 

Arkäne

Arkäne pinches the bridge of his nose, letting out a long-suffering exhale that would put martyred saints to shame. “Fashionably delayed,” he repeats, voice drier than the theoretical scroll on sand-based Mysth wards currently gathering dust in the library. “Tell me, Meadr—do you also consider singed eyebrows fashionably minimalist?”

 

He takes the bundle of tarts with the resigned air of a man accepting contraband, though his fingers linger a second too long on the waxed cloth—just to ensure it's properly sealed against the morning damp, of course.

 

The elbow nudge earns Meadr a sidelong glance sharp enough to flay parchment. “If you're here for the view,” he says, gesturing to the fog-draped pines with his free hand, “then I strongly suggest investing in spectacles. Or perhaps a map that isn't purely based on tavern rumors and dessert-related landmarks.”

 

Yet even as he speaks, he's adjusting his pace minutely to match Meadr's stride, his gloved thumb tracing the edge of the folded map in his pocket. The route he'd drawn just happened to include a detour along the ridge’s overlook—the one with the clearest vantage of the valley below.

 

Purely for observational purposes.

 

Ahead, the first faint hum of the leyline’s energy prickles against Arkäne’s senses. He tenses—subtly, reflexively—before muttering, “Try not to wander off. I’d hate to explain to the faculty why their only competent historian got himself tangled in a mystic current like a lost kite.”

 

(A lie. He’d hate talking to the faculty more.)

 

Meadr

Meadr lets out a warm, unfiltered laugh that seems to startle a nearby finch from its perch. “Spectacles?” He taps his temple again, grinning. “Ah, but where's the fun in seeing clearly when life's so much more entertaining through the lens of selective vision?” His golden eyes flicker—just for a moment—to the distant ridge overlook before returning to Arkäne with exaggerated solemnity. “I'm fairly certain some of the most profound academic discoveries were made by people who weren't looking where they were going.”

 

As the leyline's hum grows audible even to untrained senses, Meadr's playful demeanor shifts almost imperceptibly—his fingers twitch briefly near the hollow of his throat, ensuring the necklace's presence before curling loosely around the strap of his bag.

 

“Don't worry, I'll stick close,” he reassures, tone light but with an undercurrent of sincerity. “You're not getting rid of me that easily. Though—” A sudden mischievous glint. “If I do get swept away by rogue Mysth currents, at least you'll finally have proper motivation to test those emergency ward theories of yours. Think of it as... fieldwork with stakes.”

 

He reaches over and plucks one of the wrapped fig tarts from the bundle, deftly tugging the wax paper open with his teeth before extending it toward Arkäne. “Here. Fortification against hypothetical kiting-related disasters. Unless you'd prefer I sacrifice it to the leyline as an offering first?” His lips twitch. “For academic rigor, of course.”

 

Something in the way he stands—the too-casual lean, the readiness in his posture—betrays that he's attuned to every shift in the energy around them, as much as he's attuned to Arkäne's reactions. A scholar of people as much as histories.

 

 

 

Arkäne

Arkäne stares at the proffered tart like it's a particularly vexing riddle. “An offering to the leyline,” he deadpans. “Yes, because nothing appeases raw Mysth energy quite like baked fruit. Next you'll suggest we ward off a Mysth storm with aggressively cheerful small talk.”

 

Yet he plucks the tart from Meadr's fingers with practiced ease, taking a precise bite before continuing. “Though I suppose if the worst happens and you do get spirited away by the currents,”—he chews thoughtfully—“I'll at least have the consolation of finishing these in peace while composing your eulogy. 'Here lies Meadr: distractible even in the afterlife.'”

 

Ahead, the leyline's glow becomes faintly visible—a shimmer along the forest floor like heat on cobblestones. Arkäne's gaze sharpens, his posture tensing as he instinctively reaches for the Mysth currents to assess their stability. His gloves flex against empty air—habit, not necessity.

 

“You're lucky this is a dormant vein,” he mutters, more to himself than to Meadr. “Active ones would have eaten your tarts by now. And possibly your boots.”

He glances sideways at Meadr then, the barest flicker of something unreadable in his grey eyes.

 

“...Try not to prove me wrong.” A pause. “You did bring the dense bread, didn't you?”

 

Meadr

Meadr clutches his chest in mock horror, nearly stumbling over a root for dramatic emphasis. “Aggressively cheerful small talk? Me?” He presses the back of his hand to his forehead as if about to swoon. “I’ll have you know I save my aggression for debates on 7th-century trade routes—where it truly belongs.”

 

The sight of the leyline’s glow halts his theatrics. His breath catches—just a flicker—as he watches the shimmer dance along the ground, its currents invisible yet palpable to those who know how to feel them. His fingers absently brush the enchanted necklace again, a reflexive check.

 

“Oh, now who’s being dramatic?” he teases, nudging Arkäne’s elbow as he catches up. “Leylines eating boots? Please. They have standards.” He reaches into his bag with a flourish and produces the promised loaf—dense, crusty, and wrapped neatly in parchment—holding it out like a ceremonial relic. “Behold: the legendary Bread of Contingency. Guaranteed to ward off academic disasters and Mysth-induced starvation.” His grin softens as he adds, quieter, “Or at least... keep you from throttling me when I inevitably ask too many questions.”

 

He shifts closer to the leyline’s edge, just enough to feel its energy prickle against his skin—alive, humming, almost dizzying in its unseen pull—but steps back carefully before it can truly hook into him. “Dormant or not,” he muses, half to himself, “it’s still there. Waiting.” His voice drops, playful tone giving way to something more contemplative. “Wonder what it’d say if it could talk. Probably scold us both for bringing snacks to its doorstep.”

 

Then, with a deliberate pivot back to levity, he quirks a brow at Arkäne. “So. Do we just... poke it? Or is there some noble-approved method for leyline experimentation?” His eyes gleam with challenge—Go on, Helsberg. Impress me.

 

Arkäne

Arkäne lets out a slow exhale, adjusting his gloves with precise, deliberate motions. “Poke it,” he echoes, inflection perfectly flat. “Ah yes, the cornerstone of scholarly inquiry—right alongside dropping things to see if they shatter and licking unidentified Mysth residue. Truly, Meadr, your methodology leaves me breathless.”

 

He steps forward and crouches near the leyline's edge, grey eyes tracking the shimmer with the same intensity one might reserve for a venomous serpent. “Fortunately for both our sanities—and your footwear—I happen to have prepared a slightly more refined approach.”

 

From an inner pocket, he withdraws a thin copper rod etched with concentric ward sigils. His voice shifts into lecture mode, crisp and clinical: “This channels minor Mysth currents without direct skin contact. Ideally, it should allow us to test the leyline's stability without provoking it into swallowing anyone's extremities.” A pause. “Assuming, of course, no one pokes it.”

 

The corner of his mouth twitches as he extends the rod toward the shimmering boundary—just close enough for the sigils to begin glowing faintly blue. “...Though if you're really that curious about conversational leyline etiquette,” he adds, too dry to be sincere, “I'm sure we could leave you as a linguistic sacrifice.”

 

Meadr

Meadr claps his hands together, delighted. “Ah, finally! An excuse for my footwear to be spared. My poor boots were trembling in terror just moments ago.” He leans in to peer at the copper rod, golden eyes reflecting the sigils' glow—fascinated despite himself. “You know, for someone who lectured me about methodology, this does look suspiciously like poking it with extra steps.”

 

He watches the leyline react, the blue light licking up the rod like cautious flame. “Huh.” His voice drops to a hushed murmur, warm with genuine awe. “It's... quieter than I expected. Almost like it's listening.”

 

Then, just as quickly, the mischief returns. He plucks the bread from where he'd tucked it under his arm and wafts it teasingly toward the shimmering current. “Don't suppose you've got a sigil for 'politely declining baked goods' in that fancy lexicon of yours?” A pause. “Or should I brace for the dramatic tale of how Meadr Helsberg tragically lost an entire loaf to the hungry maw of the earth itself?”

 

His free hand drifts subconsciously to his throat again—safe, contained—but his grin never wavers.

 

Arkäne

Arkäne’s fingers tighten around the copper rod, the sigils flaring momentarily brighter as if mirroring his irritation. “Helsberg,” he mutters under his breath, the name sour on his tongue. “A name shared by scholars, politicians, and now, apparently, by walking tavern distractions with a bread-based death wish.”

 

He shoots Meadr a look so flat it could level a mountain. “Tell me, was there some ancestral betrayal I’m unaware of? A curse placed upon the Helsberg line condemning us to suffer one another’s company in perpetuity?” A pause. The rod twitches in his grip as the leyline’s current hums in response. “Or did you just bribe the family scribes to sneak your name onto the records?”

 

His tone is ice, but there’s no real malice in it—just the usual exasperated theater of their kinship. Still, the question lingers like a half-formed ward in the air between them: Why does sharing this with you feel less like blood obligation and more like—

 

He cuts the thought off before it can crystallize, jabbing the rod a fraction closer to the leyline. The sigils pulse sharply, casting jagged shadows across his face.

 

“—Regardless. If you get disintegrated by a Mysth backlash, I’m burning the family ledger myself. For simplicity.”

 

Meadr

Meadr clutches the loaf of bread tighter to his chest, adopting an expression of exaggerated offense—though his eyes spark with unrepentant laughter. “Bribed the scribes? Please, Arkäne,” he sighs, shaking his head. “As if I'd waste good coin on something so dull as official records when I could just—” He leans in conspiratorially, dropping his voice to a theatrical whisper, “—charm my way into the family tree.”

 

Then, stepping back just in time to avoid the leyline's restless flicker, he shrugs, feigning solemnity. “But no. No betrayal, no curses. Just the cruel twist of fate that decided the noble Helsberg bloodline needed a little... flair.” He gestures grandly to himself—his windswept hair, the half-unlaced collar of his shirt, the mischievous quirk of his lips. “You're welcome.”

 

His tone softens then, just slightly, as he tucks the bread safely back into his satchel. “Concerned for the family legacy? How touching. But I promise, I’ll leave the disintegrating to the leyline experts.” A beat. His grin sharpens. “Unless, of course, you'd prefer I stick around. Purely for scholarly comparison, naturally—which Helsberg handles Mysth with more grace? The crowd demands answers.”

 

 

 

Arkäne

Arkäne’s grip on the copper rod tightens just shy of bending the metal. “The crowd,” he repeats, voice dripping with disdain, “can take their scholarly inquiries and file them directly into the nearest incinerator.”

 

He exhales sharply through his nose, watching the leyline’s glow flicker in response to the rod’s proximity—steady, for now. “And as for flair—” His gaze flicks over Meadr’s disheveled appearance with the scrutiny of a man assessing a mildly concerning stain on his favorite tome. “—I believe the Helsberg lineage has suffered enough exuberance without you adding to its burdens. Unless you’re angling to become the family’s first historically documented cautionary tale.”

 

A pause. The rod dips lower, teasing another ripple of energy from the leyline, blue light reflecting cold in his grey eyes.

 

(“Charmed his way into the family tree.” As if it were that simple. As if the way Meadr fit—effortless as breathing, infuriating as a misprinted footnote—didn’t defy every logical principle of blood and name.)

 

He straightens abruptly. “Enough distractions. We’re here to map its resonance frequencies, not validate your delusions of genealogical grandeur.”

 

Then, quieter, almost lost beneath the leyline’s hum:

 

“And stop grinning. You look like a fox who’s just stolen an entire chicken coop.”

 

Meadr

Meadr lets out a startled laugh—bright, unguarded—that startles a pair of birds from the underbrush. “Ah, but Arkäne,” he counters, tilting his head with a grin that could only be described as foxlike, “you forget—cautionary tales are the most entertaining ones. If I'm to be immortalized in Helsberg history, I'd much prefer it be as a colorful scandal rather than some dusty footnote on leyline theory.”

 

He sidesteps as the leyline reacts to Arkäne's prodding, its shimmer curling toward the copper rod like an intrigued serpent. His fingers absently brush his necklace again, quick and unnoticed, before he folds his arms over his chest. “For the record, though—if I did steal a chicken coop, it'd be for research purposes.” His eyes gleam. “How quickly can one man outrun poultry-based vengeance? A question for the ages.”

 

Then, softer, almost affectionate: “But fine, fine. Resonances. Mapping. Scholarly solemnity.” He adjusts his stance, mimicking Arkäne's precision with exaggerated exactness—back straight, chin up, every inch the model academic before the performance cracks and he shoots Arkäne a wink. “Lead on, oh serious scholar. I promise to contain my flair for at least...” A dramatic glance at an imaginary timepiece. “...Five minutes.”

 

Pause. A sigh.

 

“Three. Okay, three minutes.”

 

Arkäne

Arkäne pinches the bridge of his nose—five seconds of quiet, was that truly too much to ask?—and exhales the long-suffering sigh of a scholar dragged to a festival against his will. “Three minutes,” he deadpans. “A record for restraint. Should I alert the Royal Archives to document this historic moment?”

 

The copper rod twitches in his grip as the leyline pulses, its energy rippling outward in response to his barely-there adjustment of Mysth flow. Blue light flickers across his sharp features, casting shadows under his eyes that make him look more like a displeased ghost than a noble researcher.

 

He pointedly ignores the way Meadr is still grinning like he’s won something.

 

“Since someone failed to bring proper notation tools,” he says, withdrawing a second, slimmer instrument from his sleeve—a stylus tuned to record Mysth resonance—“I'll be conducting the actual scientific portion of this endeavor while you stand very still and avoid further provoking the volatile energy currents.” A pause. His voice drops to a murmur barely audible over the leyline's hum.

 

“Preferably without commentary about poultry.”

 

Then, quieter still—so faint it might have been an illusion woven by the wind:

 

“...And don’t wander out of arm’s reach. Even dormant leylines dislike unexpected guests.”

 

Meadr

Meadr’s grin softens into something almost—almost—resembling earnestness for half a breath. “Arm’s reach. Noted.” He raises both hands in mock surrender, fingers splayed, though he doesn’t step away. “And I solemnly swear to keep all fowl-related hypotheses to myself.” A pause. “For at least the next three minutes.”

 

He tucks his own hands into his pockets—casual, deliberately nonchalant—but his gaze never quite leaves Arkäne’s work, tracking the stylus with keen interest. There’s a flicker of something sharper beneath his amusement, something that quickens his pulse when the leyline reacts—alive, unpredictable, beautiful in its coiled potential.

 

For once, he doesn’t voice the thought.

 

(But he stands exactly where he was told to. Close. Within reach. Because for all his teasing, he knows that tone—the one Arkäne uses when he means listen, damn it without admitting concern outright.)

 

Meadr exhales softly through his nose, watching the play of blue light across the undergrowth.

 

“...For the record,” he murmurs finally, words half-lost in the rustle of leaves, “this is exactly the kind of thing that’d make a great footnote. ‘Scholar tests resonance frequencies while beleaguered companion resists urge to reenact poultry heists.’ Future generations will weep with envy.”

 

His laughter is lighter than the breeze—quiet, warm, just shy of tender.

 

“Carry on, then. I’ll be the very picture of academic deference. Mostly.”

 

Arkäne

...The leyline hums louder, its glow intensifying briefly—as if in response to the shift in atmosphere. Arkäne does not acknowledge this. Or the warmth in Meadr's voice. Or the way his own grip tightens imperceptibly on the stylus.

 

Instead, he flicks his gaze upward just long enough to fix Meadr with a look that could wither an entire orchard. “Mostly,” he echoes, tone drier than a desert-bound scroll. “A horrifying prospect. I shudder to imagine what partial deference looks like from you.”

 

He returns his attention to the leyline's resonance patterns, but there's a fraction more focus to his movements now—precise, deliberate—as if cataloging the cadence of its energy takes precedence even over his usual sarcasm.

 

Of course, he could note aloud how rare it is for Meadr to actually listen. Or how the quiet between them never feels heavy, despite everything. But that would require admitting he'd noticed. And that would be...

 

Inconvenient.

 

So instead, he merely adjusts his stance—just enough to ensure the leyline's unstable edge doesn't drift too close—and mutters, just loudly enough to be heard:

 

“And stop breathing down my neck. You smell like cinnamon and poor decisions.”

 

Meadr

Meadr drapes a hand over his heart as if struck. “Ah, finally. My personal brand distilled into scent form.” He waves a dramatic arm through the air. “Cinnamon and Poor Decisions—coming soon to perfumeries everywhere.”

 

Yet he obligingly takes a half-step back, though not without tossing Arkäne a grin that suggests he's allowing this retreat rather than being banished. The leyline hums between them, its glow painting his foxlike features in flickering gold and blue—making him look, for a fleeting moment, more mischievous spirit than mere mortal.

 

“Funny, though,” he muses, tilting his head, “I don't recall you complaining about the cinnamon while devouring those tarts earlier. Unless—” A gasp, feigned aghast. “Was it all a ruse? Did Arkäne Helsberg tolerate my presence just for the pastries? The scandal!”

 

The playful lilt remains, but his fingers twitch slightly—restless—where they curl against his satchel strap. The leyline murmurs in response, a whisper of energy skimming the grass toward him before dissipating. Meadr's gaze flickers downward, and for half a breath, something unreadable flashes through his eyes.

 

Then he’s back to grinning, leaning to peer exaggeratedly at Arkäne’s notes. “So. Any world-shattering revelations yet, or should I start composing our application for a 'Most Patient Research Partner' medal on your behalf?”

 

Arkäne

Arkäne doesn't look up from his notations, the stylus moving with precise irritation across the parchment. “If world-shattering revelations came from standing around making inane commentary, Meadr, you'd have rewritten history twice by now.” The corner of his mouth twitches—damn him—as he underlines a resonance frequency with unnecessary force.

 

“Though if you're that desperate for validation,” he continues, voice dripping with the detached amusement of a man cataloging someone else's poor life choices, “I suppose I could draft a certificate for you. 'Congratulations on successfully not setting anything on fire for three consecutive minutes.' The guild may even frame it.”

 

The leyline pulses, throwing cobalt shadows across his notes. His shoulders tense—just slightly—before he deliberately exhales and taps the copper rod against the border again, recalibrating.

 

“...Not that you'd have space on your walls for it. Between the hypothetical genealogical forgeries and chicken-coop blueprints, of course.” A pause. Then, so dry it barely counts as acknowledgement:

 

“And stop distracting the leyline. It's starting to echo you.”

 

Meadr

Meadr gasps, pressing a hand to his chest in mock offense. “Arkāne Helsberg, are you saying my very presence is altering sacred Mysth currents? That might be the highest compliment you've ever paid me—wrapped in grumpiness, but still.” He leans in conspiratorially toward the shimmering energy, stage-whispering, “You hear that? I’m officially a scientific anomaly.”

 

Then, with an exaggerated sigh, he straightens and holds up his hands. “Fine, fine. I'll cease my nefarious leyline corruption—but only because I’m magnanimous like that. And also,” he pats his satchel meaningfully, “because that 'congratulations' certificate better come with a tart reward.”

 

He steps back, but his eyes stay sharp, watching the leyline’s reaction. There's a quiet intensity beneath the theatrics—one that only surfaces when Mysth dances this close.

 

“Next time,” he adds, grinning, “we should test whether leylines also prefer honey on their bread. For scie—.”

 

Arkäne

The leyline’s hum shifts abruptly—a sudden, discordant pulse, like a snapped string. Arkäne barely has time to stiffen before the ground beneath them shudders, the shimmering border of the current lurching outward like a cresting wave.

 

Meadr stumbles back as the earth cracks—thin, hairline fractures spiderwebbing toward his boots. His hand flies to his throat, fingers closing around the hidden necklace—

 

—And then the leyline surges.

 

A whip of raw Mysth ignites the air between them, splitting the space where Meadr had stood moments before. The backlash sends Arkäne’s copper rod clattering to the ground, its sigils flaring violently before going dark.

 

For one terrible second, everything is silence.

 

Then it writhes.

 

Ribbons of energy spiral upward, twisting into shapes that defy geometry—something half-seen, half-felt, like the afterimage of a scream. The air tastes of iron and burnt honey.

 

Arkäne’s gloves scald where he grabs Meadr’s sleeve, hauling him back another step as the fractures yawn wider. His voice is blade-sharp, stripped of all dry wit:

“Move. Now.”

 

Behind them, the trees bow away from the disturbance, their branches curling like desperate fingers. The leyline isn’t dormant anymore.

 

It’s awake.

 

Meadr

Meadr's breath hitches as his pulse roars in his ears — not fear, but something sharper, wilder, as the leyline's energy crackles against his skin like static before a storm. His fingers tighten around his necklace—still there, still hidden, still holding— but his other hand finds Arkäne’s wrist on instinct, grip just shy of bruising.

 

“Fascinating,” he breathes, voice trembling with the thrill of it all, golden eyes reflecting the leyline’s frantic dance. Then, catching the heat of Arkäne’s glare, he amends, “—I mean, right, yes, moving. Excellent plan.”

 

He doesn’t let go of Arkäne as they back away, boots skidding over upturned earth—still staring, still watching, even as survival instincts demand flight. The Mysth sings against his senses in a way it shouldn’t, in a way no dormant leyline ever has—alive, awake, hungry—

 

And then it twists. A whipcord of energy lashes out, searing a path toward them—burning, biting—

 

Meadr reacts without thinking. His free hand snaps up, palm out, and the air shudders as he pushes—not with strength, but with borrowed, reckless instinct. A ripple of foxfire flares between his fingers—raw, shimmering, wrong—

 

The collision is silent. The backlash is not.

 

The force throws them both backward as the Mysth recoils—scorched grass, singed sleeves, a smell like lightning in their lungs.

 

For one sickening second, Meadr feels the necklace’s enchantment stutter.

 

Then Arkäne is yanking him upright with a snarl, voice frayed at the edges, “What in the seven hells was that?!”

 

Meadr’s breath comes too fast. His eyes are too bright—gold bleeding into something closer to ember, pupils slitting for the barest instant before the necklace’s magic clamps down again.

 

He opens his mouth—a joke, a deflection, anything—

 

But the leyline howls. And the ground beneath them splits open.

 

Arkäne

Arkäne's breath seizes in his throat as the world fractures beneath them. He barely registers the heat of Mysth-laced wind tearing at his sleeves, the metallic tang of scorched air—all his focus narrows to the widening chasm between their boots and the crumbling edge.

 

His grip on Meadr’s wrist is ironclad.

 

“Hold on—”

 

(Not a request. Not a plea. A command, edged with something raw.)

 

Then gravity betrays them. The ledge collapses.

 

For a suspended, weightless heartbeat, they hang in the chaos—Arkäne’s free hand scrabbling for purchase on roots that snap like twigs, Meadr’s shoulder wrenched nearly from its socket. His gloves smear damp earth, fingers burning as they tear through soil—

 

—And catch.

 

A jut of stone, half-buried. Just enough.

 

They dangle over the abyss, legs kicking against open air as the leyline’s light churns below—angry, violet-white, a maw of teeth made from pure energy.

 

Arkāne’s arm screams with the strain. His gloves slip. The leyline surges upward in answer, as if scenting weakness.

 

Teeth gritted, he locks eyes with Meadr—really looks at him—foxfire fading from gold-ember irises, fear and exhilaration warring in that split-second gaze.

 

“Climb,” he rasps. “Or I swear to Quìjja, I will personally haunt you for the rest of your miserable, whimsical life.”

 

And then—just faintly, almost lost in the maelstrom—his voice cracks:

 

*“...Please.”*

 

Meadr

Meadr's pulse hammers against his ribs—air knocked from his lungs, Arkäne's grip the only tether between them and the roaring leyline below. His fingers dig into Arkäne's sleeve, tendons standing stark as wire. The necklace's enchantment sputters against his skin, the leyline's energy scraping at the edges of its warding like wildfire.

 

And Meadr grins. Wild. Bright. Terrified.

 

“Haunt me?” He wheezes a laugh, the words punched out between breaths. “You'd—ugh—never get a moment's peace.”

 

Then his free hand—palm still stinging with the ghost of foxfire—clamps over Arkäne's wrist. His other hand snaps up, thumb brushing the fraying edge of his collar, the invisible necklace humming.

 

“Hold tight—!”

 

The world folded. A lurch, a blur of pressure, the sickening weightlessness of displacement—

 

—and then they slammed into solid earth five paces back, tangled limbs on mercifully stable ground.

 

Meadr gasped, the afterburn of teleportation crackling under his skin like wildfire. His necklace burned—its enchantment straining, frayed but intact—his vision swimming with spots.

 

The leyline shrieked behind them, its violent surge crashing into empty air where they’d just fallen.

 

For a second, neither of them moved.

 

Then Arkāne shoved him back with enough force to bruise.

 

“You idiot—!” His hands fisted in Meadr’s collar, grey eyes blazing. “You have teleportation and you waited until we were hanging over the Abyss’s grinning maw to use it?!”

 

Meadr wheezed, grinning weakly through the dizziness. “Had to—savor the drama—”

 

A tremor underfoot. The leyline twisted again, its light flaring sickly green.

 

Arkāne swore and hauled them both upright, grip unrelenting. “If you ever,” he hissed, “risk yourself like that again—”

 

“Next time,” Meadr panted, leaning into him just to stay standing, “I'll aim for somewhere softer. Promise.*”

 

The earth shattered where they’d just lain.

 

They ran.

 

Arkäne

Arkäne doesn’t know which of them moves first—only that his grip on Meadr’s sleeve is ironclad, their breaths ragged and synchronized, boots pounding across a battlefield of splintered roots and collapsing soil. The leyline roars behind them, a living storm of Mysth snapping at their heels.

 

His lungs burn. His gloves are soaked through with sweat and dirt, the once-pristine embroidery on his robes now streaked with ash. Every instinct screams at him to turn and face the threat, to counter it—but the sheer, livid reality of Meadr’s exhaustion pressed against his side keeps him moving. Priorities.

 

They crest the ridge just as the leyline’s fury crests behind them—a boiling wave of energy lashing against the earth, stripping bark from trees in its wake. Arkäne doesn’t hesitate. He wrenches Meadr behind the nearest boulder, shielding him with his own body as the shockwave rips through the valley. The impact rattles his teeth, sends stones skittering past them like shrapnel—

 

And then: silence.

 

The air smells of ozone and scorched earth. The leyline, spent for now, slithers back into dormancy.

 

Arkäne exhales through clenched teeth and peels himself away, scanning Meadr for injuries with a hawk’s precision.

 

“You,” he starts, voice shredded from exertion, “are going to explain exactly what that was.” A beat. His fingers twitch toward Meadr’s collar—not to shake him, but to confirm the necklace still rests beneath the fabric. His next words are quiet, simmering.

 

“All of it.”

 

Meadr

Meadr slumps against the boulder, blinking up at Arkäne with dazed amusement despite the way his hands tremble—whether from exertion or the lingering static of magic, it's hard to tell. “Well that,” he rasps between uneven breaths, gesturing weakly back toward the wreckage, “was what happens when you bring snacks to a leyline without—augh—properly reading the invitation.”

 

Arkāne's expression could etch glass.

 

Meadr sighs, tilting his head back against the stone. His fingers brush over his throat—just once—to confirm the necklace still rests there. The enchantment hums faintly beneath his touch, threadbare from strain but holding.

 

“The teleportation bit is technically still a secret,” he admits, side-eyeing Arkāne. “Though... given the circumstances, I figured I could make an exception.” A beat. “And—”

 

The briefest hesitation, then a wince.

 

“—I may have, possibly, accidentally offended it. Just a little.”

 

Arkāne doesn't move.

 

Meadr squirms under his stare, eventually rubbing the back of his neck with a sheepish grin.

 

“...Turns out leylines don't much appreciate foxfire. Who knew?”

 

He doesn't say the rest. Doesn't have to. The half-lidded exhaustion in his eyes says it for him—I'm sorry. I wasn't thinking. Thank you for not letting go.

 

Then, with forced lightness, he nudges Arkāne's boot with his own.

 

“Still owe you that tart, though. Assuming you're not too busy drafting my epitaph.”

 

Arkäne

Arkäne stares at him for a long, dangerous moment—long enough for the adrenaline to ebb, leaving his veins flooded with cold wrath. The silence stretches taut between them, broken only by the distant crackle of dying energy and the unsteady rhythm of Meadr's breathing.

 

Then, with deliberate slowness, he reaches up and flicks Meadr hard in the forehead.

 

“Ow—!” Meadr recoils, rubbing the spot indignantly.

 

“Idiot,” Arkäne enunciates, voice like ice. “Utter. Complete idiot.” His gloves creak as his fists clench, the usually composed scholar radiating something far too close to fury. “You could have—”

 

(He doesn't finish. Doesn't elaborate on the ways Meadr might have been ripped apart. Doesn't give voice to the image burned into his mind—Meadr’s grip slipping, his body swallowed by that hungry current, nothing left but the echo of a stupid joke.)

 

Instead, his jaw works, his next words emerging thinly controlled.

 

“Foxfire. Teleportation. And you just... what, forgot to mention either until we were dangling over—” He breaks off with a sharp exhale, pinching the bridge of his nose.

 

Then, quieter, so low it's almost inaudible—

 

“...You absolute moron.”

 

His fingers flex once more before he exhales, harsh and unsteady, forcing composure back into his bones.

 

“...If you ever do that again, I am locking you in the library cellar for a month.” A beat. His voice drops, laced with warning: “With only the tax law codices for company.”

 

Meadr blinks. Then, against all reason, he laughs—bright and breathless and alive, as if they hadn't just chetted annihilation. “Well. That would be unbearable,” he concedes, grinning.

 

Arkäne stares. Then he groans, turning on his heel with a muttered curse—but not before yanking Meadr up by the collar and dragging him toward the path to the dorm. “Move,” he snaps.

 

Meadr, still grinning, does.

 

(Behind them, the scarred ground smolders.)

 

Meadr

Rhezua's fan snaps shut with an audible click as she, Owain, and Elowen watch the two stumble back into the dormitory courtyard—one glaring, one still covered in dirt and grinning like a fool.

 

“Well,” she remarks, voice smooth as poisoned honey, “I suppose this explains the tremors. Did you two manage to offend an entire leyline, or was this just your usual brand of recklessness?”

 

Owain leans forward, white braid swinging, eyes gleaming with delight. “Nay, tell us truly—did ye wrestle a storm-spirit? Leap into the abyss for dramatic principle?”

 

Elowen, arms crossed, merely arches a brow—“Or did you finally test if fire and water truly cancel out?”—a pointed glance at Meadr's singed sleeves and Arkäne's damp, mud-streaked robes.

 

Meadr opens his mouth—likely to spin some exaggerated tale—but Arkäne cuts in first, icy and clipped.

 

“Tributary displacement test gone awry. Unstable current. No casualties. Move along.” His tone brooks no argument, and his gloved grip on Meadr's collar tightens just enough to be a warning.

 

Meadr, ever the contrarian, coughs something suspiciously like “—mostly—” under his breath before flashing the group a reassuring (if slightly singed) smile. “Just a bit of fieldwork! You know how it is. Mysth, uh... surprises.”

 

Owain and Elowen exchange glances. Rhezua's fan reopens, slow and deliberate.

 

“So. Foxfire discharge, then,” she muses, lips curling.

 

Meadr goes rigid.

 

Arkäne's expression darkens. “Who said anything about—”

 

“Please,” Rhezua sniffs, turning away. “I do have eyes.”

 

Silence. Meadr's grin falters for a fraction of a second before his laugh covers it—too quick, too loud.

 

Owain claps his hands. “Brilliant! Next time, do warn us before ye upturn a valley. We could've placed bets!”

 

Elowen smirks. “Aye. 'How long until they set something on fire' seems a fair wager.”

 

Arkäne exhales, long-suffering, and drags Meadr toward the dorm steps—ignoring the whispers sparking in their wake.

 

Meadr, despite it all, still has the gall to wave.

 

(Behind them, the rumor mill ignites.)

 

Arkäne

(Later, in Arkäne’s dorm room…)

 

Arkäne shuts the door behind them with a sharp click, wards flaring to life as he turns on Meadr with a look that could freeze fire.

 

“You foxfire-touched, leyline-taunting, self-sacrificing—” He cuts himself off with a stiff inhale, fingers twitching like he wants to strangle Meadr but hasn’t decided if he’d prefer to do so bare-handed or with a well-aimed Mysth construct.

 

Meadr, for his part, slumps onto Arkäne’s desk with all the grace of a half-drowned alley cat, still grinning—though there’s something beneath it now, something taut and guilty.

 

“Ah, come on.” He flicks a loose thread from his ruined sleeve. “You think Rhezua actually knows, or was she just—?”

 

“Don’t.” Arkäne’s voice is steel-edged. “We are not doing this.”

 

Meadr’s fingers toy absently with his necklace—still there, still intact, but strained. When he looks up, his expression is uncharacteristically serious. “...She’d only have to pull one thread.” His voice is softer now, stripped of its usual levity. “One thread, and it unravels.”

 

Arkäne exhales through his nose, fists still clenched, before snatching a spare robe from his wardrobe and tossing it at Meadr. “Then stop unraveling in front of her,” he snaps, but the bite is half-hearted, the fury already cooling into something more complicated.

 

Silence settles between them. Outside, the distant hum of the leyline—still unsettled—presses against the wards like a wolf testing a fence.

 

Arkäne rubs his temples. “You are impossible.”

 

Meadr smirks, but it’s a tired thing.

 

“Takes one to know one.”

 

(Neither of them mentions the way Meadr still trembles—just faintly—from exertion.

 

Neither of them mentions the way Arkäne hesitates before turning his back to him, as if half-expecting him to vanish mid-breath.)

 

Tomorrow, they’ll have to answer questions. Tomorrow, Rhezua will be watching. Tomorrow, the leyline’s unsettled energy might still coil beneath the earth like a living thing, waiting.

 

But for now—grounded, bruised, alive—they let the quiet linger.

 

Meadr, because he can’t help himself, breaks it first.

 

“...So. About that tart.”

 

Arkāne throws a pillow at his head.
